6 a) Write a program to embed internal and external javascript in a webpage.

Aim:Write a program to embed internal and external javascript in a webpage.

Description:

• Demonstrates use of internal and external JavaScript in a webpage.

• Internal script is written inside <script> tags within the HTML file.

• External script is stored in a separate .js file and linked using <script src="">.

• Two buttons are used to run internal and external JavaScript functions separately.

• Shows how to organize and execute scripts in different ways.

Program:

script.js:

// script.js

function greetExternal() {

alert("Hello from External JavaScript!");

}

jsdemo.html:

<!DOCTYPE html>

<html>

<head>

<title>Internal and External JavaScript</title>

 <!-- Link to external JavaScript file -->

<script src="script.js"></script>

<!-- Internal JavaScript -->

<script>

function greetInternal() {

alert("Hello from Internal JavaScript!");

}

</script>

</head>

<body>

<h1>Welcome to JavaScript Demo</h1>

<button onclick="greetInternal()">Click for Internal Script</button>

<button onclick="greetExternal()">Click for External Script</button>

</body>

</html>

Output:



b) Write a program to explain the different ways for displaying output.

Aim:Write a program to explain the different ways for displaying output.

Description:

Program:

<!DOCTYPE html>

<html>

<head>

<title>Output Methods in JavaScript</title>

<script>

// Method 1: alert() - Popup alert box

function showAlert() {

alert("This is an alert box!");

}

// Method 2: console.log() - Logs output to browser console

function showConsoleLog() {

console.log("This is a console log message.");

}

// Method 3: document.write() - Writes directly to the web page

function showDocumentWrite() {

document.write("<p>This is written using document.write().</p>");

}

// Method 4: innerHTML - Outputs content into an HTML element

function showInnerHTML() {

document.getElementById("outputArea").innerHTML = "This is output using innerHTML.";

}

</script>

</head>

<body>

<h2>JavaScript Output Methods</h2>

<button onclick="showAlert()">Show Alert Box</button><br><br>

<button onclick="showConsoleLog()">Show Console Log</button><br><br>

<button onclick="showDocumentWrite()">Use document.write()</button><br><br>

<button onclick="showInnerHTML()">Use innerHTML</button><br><br>

<div id="outputArea" style="color: blue; font-weight: bold;"></div>

</body>

</html>


6 c) Write a program to explain the different ways for taking input.

Aim:Write a program to explain the different ways for taking input.

Description:

• This program explains different ways of taking input in JavaScript.

• Prompt() is used to get input directly from a popup dialog box.

• Textbox/Input field allows users to enter data in the webpage.

• Console can be used by developers to take or view input through browser tools.

• It helps understand multiple input methods for different use cases.

Program:

<html>

<head>

<style>

table {

border: 1;

width: 50%;

margin-top: 20px;

}

</style>

</head>

<body>

<h1>Different ways to take Input in Javascript</h1>

<form onsubmit="registrationFun(event)">

<label>Name</label><br>

<input type="text" id="name" name="name" ><br>

<label>Email Id: </label><br>

<input type="email" id="email" name="email" ><br>

<label>Date of Birth</label><br>

<input type="date" id="dob" name="dob" ><br>

<label>Address</label><br>

<textarea id="address" name="address" ></textarea><br>

<p>Gender:</p>

<input type="radio" id="male" name="gender" value="male">

<label>Male</label><br>

<input type="radio" id="female" name="gender" value="female">

<label>Female</label><br>

 <p>Languages Known:</p>

<input type="checkbox" id="telugu" name="language" value="telugu">

<label>Telugu</label><br>

<input type="checkbox" id="english" name="language" value="english">

<label>English</label><br>

<input type="checkbox" id="hindi" name="language" value="hindi">

<label>Hindi</label><br>

<input type="checkbox" id="tamil" name="language" value="tamil">

<label>Tamil</label><br>

<input type="checkbox" id="spanish" name="language" value="spanish">

<label>Spanish</label><br>

<p>Country:</p>

<select id="country">

<option>Select</option>

<option value="india">India</option>

<option value="china">China</option>

<option value="japan">Japan</option>

</select><br><br>

<button>SignIn </button>

<button onclick="loginFun()" >LogIn</button>

</form>

<div id="result"></div>
<script> 

// Method 1: prompt() - Takes input using a dialog box

function loginFun()

{

username=prompt("ENTER USERNAME");

password=prompt("ENTER PASSWORD");

alert("Login Successful" + "username : " + username + " password : " + password);

}

<!-- Method 2: Input field + DOM access -->

function registrationFun(event)

{

event.preventDefault();

name=document.getElementById("name").value; 

 mail=document.getElementById("email").value;

dob=document.getElementById("dob").value;

address=document.getElementById("address").value;

country=document.getElementById("country").value;

language=document.getElementsByName("language");

selectedLanguage=[];

for ( i = 0; i < language.length; i++)

{

if (language[i].checked)

{

selectedLanguage.push(language[i].value);

}

}

gender = document.getElementsByName("gender");

for ( i = 0; i < gender.length; i++)

{

if (gender[i].checked) {

var selectedGender = gender[i].value;

break;

}

}

output =

`<strong>Your Registration Details:</strong>

<table>

<tr><td>Name</td> <td>${name}</td></tr>

<tr><td>Email</td> <td>${mail}</td></tr>

<tr><td>Date of Birth</td> <td>${dob}</td></tr>

<tr><td>Address</td> <td>${address}</td></tr>

<tr><td>Country</td> <td>${country}</td></tr>

<tr><td>Language</td> <td>${selectedLanguage}</td></tr>

<tr><td>Gender</td> <td>${selectedGender }</td></tr>

</table>

`; 

document.getElementById("result").innerHTML=output;

}

</script>

</body>

</html>


6 d) Create a webpage which uses prompt dialogue box to ask a voter for his name and age. 

Display the information in table format along with either the voter can vote or not.

Aim:Create a webpage which uses prompt dialogue box to ask a voter for his name and age. Display the 

information in table format along with either the voter can vote or not.

Description:

• This program asks the user for their name and age using the prompt() dialog box.

• The entered details are then displayed in a table format on the webpage.

• Based on the age, the program checks if the user is eligible to vote (age ≥ 18).

• If eligible, it shows “Can Vote”; otherwise, it shows “Cannot Vote”.

• This demonstrates how to take user input using prompts and display the information 

dynamically in an HTML table.

Program:

<!DOCTYPE html>

<html>

<head>

<title>Voter Eligibility Check</title>

<style>

table {

border-collapse: collapse;

margin-top: 20px;

width: 50%;

}

th, td {

border: 1px solid black;

padding: 10px;

text-align: center;

}

th {

background-color: #f2f2f2;

}

</style>

<script>

function checkVoter() {

let name = prompt("Enter your name:");

let age = prompt("Enter your age:");

age = parseInt(age); // Convert age to number

 let status = (age >= 18) ? "Eligible to Vote" : "Not Eligible to Vote";

// Insert data into the table

document.getElementById("voterName").innerText = name;

document.getElementById("voterAge").innerText = age;

document.getElementById("voterStatus").innerText = status;

}

</script>

</head>

<body onload="checkVoter()">

<h2>Voter Information</h2>

<table>

<tr>

<th>Name</th>

<th>Age</th>

<th>Voter Status</th>

</tr>

<tr>

<td id="voterName"></td>

<td id="voterAge"></td>

<td id="voterStatus"></td>

</tr>
</table>

</body>

</html>

Output


